</administrative_district>
</region>
 (<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../546/17546.xml">
Louvre</link>)
</caption>
</image>
</p>

</ss1>
</sec>
<sec>
<st>
Gallo-Roman art</st>
<p>

Roman culture introduced a new phase of anthropomorphized sculpture to the Gaulish community,<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%225%22])">5</ref> synthesized with  Celtic traditions of refined metalworking, a rich body of urbane Gallo-Roman silver developed, which the upheavals of the second and fifth centuries motivated hiding away in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../343/654343.xml">
hoard</link>s, which have protected some pieces of Gallo-Roman silver, from villas and temple sites, from the universal destruction of precious metalwork in circulation. The exhibition of Gallo-Roman silver highlighted specifically Gallo-Roman silver from the treasures found at  Chaourse (Mâcon), Graincourt-lès-Havrincourt (Pas de Calais),Notre-Dame d'Allençon (Maine-et-Loire), and Rethel (Ardennes, found in 1980).<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%226%22])">6</ref>
</p>
</sec>
<sec>
<st>
Gallo-Roman sites</st>
<p>

The two more Romanised of the three Gauls were bound together in a network of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../898/25898.xml">
Roman road</link>s that linked cities.  <site wordnetid="108651247" confidence="0.8">
